{{Infobox musical artist | name = Carlota Jaramillo | background = solo_singer | image = MUSEO-CASA DE CARLOTA JARAMILLO "LA REINA DE LA CANCIÓN NACIONAL" (39986307341) (cropped).jpg | image_size = 250px | birth_name = María Isabel Carlota Jaramillo | alias = ''La Reina de la Canción Nacional'' | birth_date = {{birth date|1904|07|09}} | birth_place = [[Calacalí]], [[Ecuador]] | death_date = {{death date and age|1987|12|10|1904|07|09}} | death_place = [[Quito]], [[Ecuador]] | genre = [[Pasillo (música)|Pasillo]], [[Pasacalles]] | occupation = Singer | instrument = [[vocal]], [[classical guitar]] | years_active = [[1922]] – [[1987]] }}
'''María Isabel Carlota Jaramillo''', stage name '''Carlota Jaramillo''' (9 July 1904 – 10 December 1987) was an [[Ecuador]]ian ''[[pasillo]]'' singer, known as "''La Reina de la Canción Nacional''" (Queen of National Song).
==Early life== Jaramillo was born in Calacalí, in 1904. Her parents, Isaac Jaramillo Jaramillo and Natalia Jaramillo, were farmers. She grew in a musical family, one of her uncles and her maternal grandfather were musicians. Carlota studied in her hometown primary school and attended the “Manuela Cañizares” [[normal school]] in Quito to graduate as a teacher.
==Career== In 1922 Jaramillo and her sister won a song contest at the Teatro Sucre in Quito. They were the only women in the competition.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.eluniverso.com/2004/07/06/0001/259/842B2FF452B343E7822F178144E03ABE.html|title=Carlota Jaramillo, la reina del pasillo ecuatoriano - JUL. 06, 2004 - Música - Historicos - EL UNIVERSO|last=eluniverso.com.|website=www.eluniverso.com|access-date=2018-08-08}}</ref> After that Jaramillo followed the musical career. She recorded her first disc in 1938, the pasillo ''Amor Grande y Lejano. In 1942 ''she recorded with Luis Alberto Valencia'', Sendas Distintas'', composed by her husband, Jorge Araujo Chiriboga.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elcomercio.com/tendencias/sendas-distintas-historia-amor.html|title=Sendas Distintas, la historia de amor de la Reina del Pasillo|website=El Comercio|language=es-LA|access-date=2018-08-08}}</ref> Other hit songs by her include ''La ingratitud'', ''Sombras'', ''Honda pena'', and ''Para mi tus recuerdos.''
== Death and homages == Jaramillo died on 10 December 1987 of cerebral traumatisms after a fall in her home. She got a funeral with full honors from the Ecuatorian society. A monument in her honor was built in Calacalí in 1972.<ref>[http://www.diccionariobiograficoecuador.com/tomos/tomo23/j1.htm Pérez Pimentel, Rodolfo, «Carlota Jaramillo de Araujo», ''Diccionario Biográfico del Ecuador'', acceso 2011]</ref> Her house was transformed into a museum in 2004.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.elcomercio.com/actualidad/quito/calacali-hay-museo-carlota-jaramillo.html|title=En Calacalí hay un museo sobre Carlota Jaramillo|website=El Comercio|language=es-LA|access-date=2018-08-08}}</ref>
