{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2014}} {{Infobox newspaper | name = Esti Budapest | logo = | image = Esti-Budapest-6-October-1956.jpg | image_size = 200px | caption = ''Esti Budapest'', 6 October 1956 | type = [[Evening newspaper]] | format = | owners = | founder = | publisher = | editor = | chiefeditor = | assoceditor = | maneditor = | newseditor = | managingeditordesign = | campuseditor = | campuschief = | opeditor = | sportseditor = | photoeditor = | staff = | foundation = 2 April 1952 | political = | language =[[Hungarian language|Hungarian]] | ceased publication = 23 October 1956 | headquarters = [[Budapest]] | circulation = | sister newspapers = | ISSN = | oclc = 34883422 | website = }}
'''''Esti Budapest''''' (meaning ''Evening Budapest'' in English) was a [[Hungary|Hungarian]] newspaper. It was published daily (except Sundays) from 2 April 1952 to 23 October 1956.
==History and profile== ''Esti Budapest'' was first published on 2 April 1952.<ref name=rcg/> The paper was the successor of ''[[Vilagossag]]''.<ref name=rcg/> It was an evening newspaper and featured mostly leisure- and culture-related news.<ref>{{cite book|author=Karl William Brown|title=Regulating Bodies: Everyday Crime and Popular Resistance in Communist Hungary, 1948--1956|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=RMQLxXnBD3IC&pg=PA190|accessdate=26 December 2014|year=2007|publisher=ProQuest|isbn=978-0-549-38084-9|page=22}}</ref> The paper was the organ of the [[Budapest]] Party Committee of the [[Hungarian Working People's Party]] and the Budapest City Council.<ref name=rcg/>
''Esti Budapest'' ceased publication on 23 October 1956 and was later replaced by ''[[Esti Hírlap]]''.<ref name=rcg>{{cite web|author=R. G. Carlton|title=Newspapers from East Central and Southeastern Europe|url=http://lcweb2.loc.gov/service/gdc/scd0001/2010/20100111001ne/20100111001ne.pdf|publisher=Library of Congress|accessdate=26 December 2014|location=Washington, DC|date=1965}}</ref>
