{{redirect|Stormy Nights|the 1995 hard rock song|Stormy Nights (song)}} {{distinguish|In Stormy Nights}}
{{Infobox operational plan | name = Operation Stormy Nights | partof = | image = | caption = | scope = | type = [[Sting operation]] | location = [[Oklahoma]], United States | coordinates = | map_type = | latitude = | longitude = | map_size = | map_caption = | map_label = | planned = | planned_by = | objective = To free [[Minor (law)|minors]] from [[forced prostitution]] and arrest their traffickers | target = | date = 2004 | time = | time-begin = | time-end = | timezone = | executed_by = {{Flagicon image|Flag of the Federal Bureau of Investigation.svg|size=23px}}[[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] | outcome = 23 girls rescued, 12 traffickers arrested | casualties = | fatalities = | injuries = }}
'''Operation Stormy Nights''' was an early major anti-[[Human trafficking|human-trafficking]] operation by the [[Federal Bureau of Investigation]] (FBI).<ref name=Stone7>Rhodes, p. 7.</ref> It took place in [[Oklahoma]], [[United States]] and brought to light [[organized crime]] networks trafficking female [[Minor (law)|minors]] along [[United States Numbered Highways]], where the girls were [[Forced prostitution|forcibly prostituted]] to [[truck driver]]s.<ref>{{Cite book|page=248|title=Human Trafficking: A Global Perspective|author=Louise Shelley|publisher=[[Cambridge University Press]]|year=2010|isbn=1139489771}}</ref>
==Onset of the operation== The operation was undertaken in 2004 and resulted in the release of 23 girls from [[Prostitution of children|child prostitution]].<ref>{{Cite web|title=Human Trafficking in Oklahoma|publisher=Harrah Police Department|url=http://www.harrahpolicedept.com/Human-trafficking.html|accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref> Twelve [[Procuring (prostitution)|pimps]] were arrested.<ref>{{Cite news|work=Oklahoma City Community College Pioneer|title=Human sex trafficking state issue|date=December 9, 2011|author=Morgan Beard|url=http://pioneer2010.occc.edu/index.php/features/60-feature/1671-human-sex-trafficking-state-issue|accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref> Most of these traffickers' victims were between 12 and 17 years of age.<ref>{{Cite journal|journal=[[People (magazine)|People]]|title=Nightmare at the Truck Stop|author=Alex Tresniowski|date=May 1, 2006|volume=65|issue=17|url=http://www.people.com/people/archive/article/0,,20062080,00.html|accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref> [[Lieutenant]] Alan Prince said that operations like Stormy Nights "are difficult because the girls are always on the move... and when you find them, it's hard to talk to them."<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[The Topeka Capital-Journal]]|title=Sex trafficking charges filed|date=January 22, 2005|url=http://cjonline.com/stories/012205/kan_sextrafficing.shtml|accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref> This [[sting operation]] was headed by FBI agent [[Mike Beaver (FBI agent)|Mike Beaver]], who was working as an [[Undercover operation|undercover agent]].<ref name=Connecticut/>
==Sex trafficking== One of the human trafficking victims rescued in Stormy Nights was a girl named Angie.<ref name=Stone7/> Beaver called Angie "a normal, typical American teenager."<ref name=Connecticut>{{Cite AV media|title=Human Trafficking: Modern Day Slavery|date=April 17, 2013|publisher=[[Connecticut Public Radio]]|author=[[John Dankosky]]|url=http://www.yourpublicmedia.org/content/wnpr/human-trafficking-modern-day-slavery|accessdate=August 21, 2013}}</ref> Angie, from [[Wichita, Kansas|Wichita]], [[Kansas]], was being [[Prostitution|prostituted]] with another girl, Melissa, in the [[Midwestern United States]].<ref name=Stone8>Rhodes, p. 8.</ref> They were both teenagers at the time.<ref name=Kansas/>
==Documented as a short film== Angie was later interviewed in the [[documentary film]] ''[[Not My Life]]'', in which Angie explains how she and Melissa were expected to engage in [[sexual intercourse]] with truck drivers at a [[truck stop]] and [[Theft|steal]] their money. Angie said that, while looking through one of these drivers' wallets, she found pictures of the man's grandchildren and realized that he was old enough to be hers and Melissa's grandfather. She recounts this story disgustedly and almost crying, and says, "I wanted to die."<ref name=Kansas>{{Cite news|work=Kansas City infoZine|title=Lucy Liu and Others Advocate Against Trafficking Sex, Domestic Workers|author=Cindy Von Quednow|date=September 21, 2009|url=http://www.infozine.com/news/stories/op/storiesView/sid/37553/#|accessdate=August 1, 2013}}</ref> Beaver also appears in the film, saying, "It's not just truck drivers. We're seeing them purchased and abused by both white collar and blue collar individuals."<ref name=Stone8/> [[Robert Bilheimer]], the film's director, said that Angie did not fit the [[stereotype]] for a girl at risk of being sexually trafficked; she was from the [[Heartland (United States)|heartland]], attended a [[private school]] and, when her parents divorced, she began [[acting out]] as a way of [[Attention seeking|seeking attention]]. A man [[Child abduction|abducted]] her when she was 12 years old, violated the [[Mann Act]] by transporting her to another state, and began trafficking her sexually.<ref name=Connecticut/> While being trafficked, Angie was expected to engage in 40 sex acts every night, charging $50 for [[oral sex]], $60 for [[vagina]]l sex, and $70 for both.<ref name=Stone7/> Her trafficker threatened to kill her if she refused to perform these acts.<ref name=Connecticut/> Bilheimer said that the truck drivers Angie was expected to service either did not know or did not want to know what would happen to her if she did not give all of the money she earned to her pimp.<ref name=Stone46/> Another girl who was rescued in Stormy Nights, one of Angie's friends, was sent to a [[district attorney]] (DA) in order to facilitate the preparation of her [[testimony]], and the DA told the girl that he wouldn't talk to her until she had performed [[fellatio]] on him.<ref name=Stone46/> Bilheimer said that, while there is no way of being certain how many girls like Angie are being sexually trafficked, "diligent people out there have arrived at a bare minimum figure of... one hundred thousand girls, eight to fifteen [performing] ten sex acts a day" adding up to "a billion unpunished crimes of sexual violence on an annual basis." While Bilheimer interviewed Beaver at a Midwestern truck stop like the ones at which Angie was trafficked, someone wrote "Fuck you, asshole!" in the dirt on Beaver's car. Bilheimer said that this act demonstrated that many truck drivers hate law enforcement, although he said that "there are some good truckers out there,"<ref name=Stone46>Rhodes, p. 46.</ref> like those who are part of [[Truckers Against Trafficking]], an [[List of organizations opposing human trafficking|organization opposing human trafficking]] by [[Consciousness raising|raising awareness]] on the subject among truck drivers.<ref>{{Cite web|title=''Not My Life'' Discussion Guide|publisher=World Without Genocide|url=http://worldwithoutgenocide.org/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/Not-My-Life-Discussion-Guide.pdf|accessdate=August 16, 2013}}</ref> When news of Stormy Nights was made public, there was a strong public response across the country, so the FBI established "Innocence Lost", a new department working to free children from prostitution.<ref>{{Cite news|work=[[Oklahoma Gazette]]|title=Human network|author=C.G. Niebank|date=September 7, 2011|url=http://www.okgazette.com/oklahoma/article-12912-human-network.html|accessdate=September 5, 2013}}</ref>
