[[File:Constantin Jiquidi - Aud̦ind aşa văcarul (Păcală, de P. Dulfu).JPG|thumb|Sentenced to [[Drowning#Capital punishment|death by drowning]], Păcală tricks the ignorant cowherd into taking his place in the [[burlap]] sack. Illustration by {{Interlanguage link multi|Constantin Jiquidi|ro}}, [[Petre Dulfu]] version (1894)]]

'''Păcală''' ([[Romanian language|Romanian]], from ''a păcăli'', "to dupe"; sometimes rendered '''Pâcală''' or '''Pîcală''') is a fictional character in [[Romanian folklore]], [[Romanian literature|literature]] and [[Romanian humor|humor]]. An irreverent young man, seemingly a peasant, he reserves contempt and irony for the village authorities (whether priest, [[boyar]] or judge), but often plays the fool. Several derivative works codify the various versions of ''Păcală'' anecdotes. Examples include: ''Pâcală'', by [[Ion Creangă]]; ''Păcală în satul lui'' ("Păcală in His Village") by [[Ioan Slavici]]; ''Isprăvile lui Păcală'' ("Păcală's Achievements") by [[Petre Dulfu]]; and ''Întâmplările lui Păcală'' ("The Adventures of Păcală"), part of ''[[Legende sau basmele românilor]]''.

''Păcală'' legends also served to inspire other creations, from the eponymous satirical magazine put out by [[Pantazi Ghica]] in the 1860s to [[Constantin S. Nicolăescu-Plopșor]]'s 1960s sequel ''Tivisoc şi Tivismoc'' ("Tivisoc and Tivismoc"). He is the main protagonist in two [[Cinema of Romania|Romanian films]], both written and directed by [[Geo Saizescu]]; and inspired artist [[Sandu Florea]] to create his first comic strip (1968).

